---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy Learning Center — Journal Foundation"
  description="Explore privacy literacy resources on metadata, encryption, decentralization, and anonymization for every skill level."
>
  <main class="learn-page">
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>Privacy Learning Center</h1>
        <p class="lead">Understand digital privacy, security, and sovereignty—whether or not you ever use our protocols.</p>
        <p>
          Journal Foundation publishes education for everyone: students, organizers, policymakers, technologists,
          and people just beginning to question how their data is used. Start with the essentials, then dive into
          advanced topics when you are ready.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="why-privacy">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Why Privacy Matters</h2>
        <div class="content-grid">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Surveillance Capitalism</h3>
            <p>
              Advertising networks harvest every click, location ping, and purchase. They build behavioral profiles that
              predict what we do next—and sell that influence to the highest bidder.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Metadata Exposure</h3>
            <p>
              Even when messages are encrypted, metadata reveals who you talk to, when, and how often. Patterns expose
              relationships, routines, and vulnerabilities.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Algorithmic Manipulation</h3>
            <p>
              Recommendation systems decide what we see. Without control, a handful of companies can steer information,
              culture, and politics at population scale.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concepts">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Essential Concepts</h2>
        <div class="concept-list">
          <article class="concept">
            <h3>What Is Metadata?</h3>
            <p>
              Metadata is data about data—who sent a message, when it was sent, how large it was, where it originated.
              Think of the outside of an envelope: even without reading the letter, you know the sender, recipient,
              and timing.
            </p>
            <p>
              Attackers combine these clues to map social graphs or identify whistleblowers. Protecting privacy
              requires minimizing both content and metadata exposure.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="concept">
            <h3>What Is End-to-End Encryption?</h3>
            <p>
              End-to-end encryption means only the sender and recipient can read the contents of a message. Services like
              Signal and WhatsApp use it to prevent eavesdropping by network operators or governments.
            </p>
            <p>
              But encryption doesn't hide metadata. If you text someone every day at 10pm, that pattern is still visible.
              True privacy pairs encryption with anonymization.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="concept">
            <h3>What Is Decentralization?</h3>
            <p>
              Decentralization distributes control across many operators. Projects like Mastodon and the Fediverse let
              communities run their own servers rather than relying on one company.
            </p>
            <p>
              It's a powerful step, but not the final answer. Without metadata protection, decentralized systems can still
              leak who is talking to whom—and that can be enough to cause harm.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="concept">
            <h3>What Is Anonymization?</h3>
            <p>
              Anonymization hides the link between people and their data flows. Techniques include traffic mixing,
              blind relays, and capability-based access so observers can't map relationships or download everything at once.
            </p>
            <p>
              Journal Foundation focuses on anonymization because decentralization alone leaves users exposed to
              surveillance capitalism and nation-state adversaries.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="guides">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Practical Guides</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>How to evaluate a "privacy-focused" app</li>
          <li>How to read a privacy policy</li>
          <li>How to enable Global Privacy Control</li>
          <li>How to use Signal safely</li>
          <li>How to understand app permissions</li>
          <li>How to protect yourself from surveillance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="advanced">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Advanced Topics</h2>
        <div class="content-grid">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Understanding Threat Models</h3>
            <p>Start with the question: "Who am I protecting against?" Then map capabilities and safeguards.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Download-now, Decrypt-later</h3>
            <p>
              Quantum decryption plus bulk data seizure means encrypted archives today can become readable tomorrow. Minimize
              what leaves your vault.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>"I Have Nothing to Hide" Is Wrong</h3>
            <p>
              Privacy isn't about secrets. It's about dignity, autonomy, and the freedom to experiment without constant
              observation.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>How Influence Works at Scale</h3>
            <p>
              Data brokers and recommendation engines weaponize attention. Learn how targeted narratives move markets and
              elections.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="resources">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Resources</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/whitepapers">Journal Foundation whitepapers</a></li>
          <li><a href="/stack">Learn about the protocol stack</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.eff.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.torproject.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tor Project</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.privacyguides.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Privacy Guides</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <style>
    .learn-page {
      padding-bottom: var(--space-3xl);
    }

    .hero {
      padding: var(--space-3xl) 0;
    }

    .lead {
      font-size: var(--step-1);
      color: var(--color-text-primary);
      margin-top: var(--space-md);
    }

    section {
      padding: var(--space-3xl) 0;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
    }

    .content-grid {
      display: grid;
      gap: var(--space-xl);
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    }

    .card {
      background: var(--void-lighter);
      border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
      padding: var(--space-xl);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: var(--space-sm);
    }

    .concept-list {
      display: grid;
      gap: var(--space-2xl);
    }

    .concept {
      background: var(--void-lighter);
      border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
      padding: var(--space-xl);
      border: 1px solid rgba(45, 125, 255, 0.15);
      display: grid;
      gap: var(--space-sm);
    }

    .guides ul,
    .resources ul {
      list-style: disc;
      padding-left: var(--space-xl);
      color: var(--color-text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.7;
    }

    .guides li + li,
    .resources li + li {
      margin-top: var(--space-xs);
    }

    @media (max-width: 720px) {
      .card,
      .concept {
        padding: var(--space-lg);
      }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
